title: For Sale/Trade:  Dan Wesson 357 Pistol Pack RARE and Beautiful Condition
postcontent:
Selling my Dan Wesson 357 Magnum pistol pack. The pistol pack includes all the barrels that were available for the gun when they were made. These packs are getting harder and harder to find, especially ones that are in great condition and havent had the barrels shot out. The revolver is in amazing condition, almost new aside from the fact that I shot the gun a couple times. 

The 2.5, 4, 6, and 8 in barrels all included are in beautiful shape, with no scratches, marks, or corrosion of any type. 

The kit includes a spare grip (I believe its aftermarket made by PACHMAYR), the tool for changing the barrel, the original allen key, and the feeler guage (used to make sure the barrel is installed correctly). It also includes all the sights that originally came with it. Yellow, White, and Red. Red ones are installed on the revolver frame, and each of the replacement barrels, making for a total of 5 red barrel sights and 1 red frame sight. There are only 2 sights (1 frame, 1 barrel) for the white and yellow. None are missing, they just came with extra red sights.

Things that were not originally included but I have added are. A bore brush for cleaning, and a thread tap for the revolver frame. Ive never had to use the tap, but because it was a special order item, I ordered it just in case I ever needed it. I didnt want to run into a situation where I needed it, then have to wait a week for one to come in the mail.

Also included are the original Dan Wesson revolver instructions. Everything from a description of the revolver, maintenance and cleaning information, and how to change the barrels are covered. The instructions are in perfect condition as well and I keep them in a little case.

I DO NOT have the belt buckle and or patch that they came with.

Asking 1250. I do not NEED to sell it, so no low ball offers. Also, if your interested, have the cash to spend. Save the both of us the time if your not a serious buyer with cash to spend. I dont want endless emails and text messages just for you to have to ask your wife/husband if they will allow you to buy it. BE SERIOUS

You must be at least 21 and have an ID to purchase this revolver from me. You will also have to sign a bill of sale that includes a copy of your ID. I am not a dealer/vendor, this is only for my personal records and piece of mind. Shipping would be possible from my ffl to yours. Ive never shipped a gun before, but if it makes the deal, id be willing to ship it through my local ffl to yours.

postcontent:
For "Trade Only" is my Little Ruger LCR, Chambered in .38 Special and +P Rated

This is one awesome little revolver. One of the most significant changes in revolver design when it was first introduced at the Ruger, New Hampshire Plant. Yes, this is an all American Made small revolver designed with Personal Protection in mind. It is not a Range Toy.
Don't mistake this as just another Small-Frame Snubnose Revolver. It is extremely lightweight at only 13.5 ounces it is easy to conceal and a pleasure to carry. It is basically the same size as the S&W Chief Special and the Taurus Model 85 and fits in the same style and size holster.
They were in fact, the first to create the Polymer Framed Revolver and now others are following suit. If you know Ruger, then you know that they are known for their durability and they did not skimp on this little protective device. There are several versions of this little gem, chambered in .357 magnum, .22LR, and even 9mm. I recently purchased the 9mm Version and that is why I am letting this one go.

* 1-7/8" Barrel

title: For Sale:  Rare 480 Code Walther P.38
postcontent: When the German Army completed its P.38 testing with the end of the Fourth Variation Zero Series model, the P.38 was officially adopted as the German Army's standard side arm. Following this official adoption of the P.38, Walther produced the first true military P.38 known as the 480 Code P.38. The First Variation of the 480 Code of the P.38, also known as the Fourth Developmental Stage, was the last stage of research and development on this model, even though the weapon had already been officially adopted. The serial number for the First Variation Code of the P.38 begins at number 1 and progressed sequentially up through approximately number 6830, with production dates for these pistols beginning in late July, early August 1940 until late September, early October 1940.This particular 480 Code P.38 is an early serial number 646, with an estimated production date in early August 1940. This P.38 appears to have been a Russian Capture weapon as evidence by the “X,” (crossed rifles) above the serial number on the left side of the slide. From the front left portion of the slide is the nomenclature stamp “P.38.” Just to the right of the P.38 stamp is the “480” Code stamp, with the numerals measuring approximately 2.90mm tall and 6.02mm in length. The top of the number “4” is the correct "open top" style as opposed to the serial number “4” which is correctly the "closed top" style. The safety lever, which is blued, has the correct eagle over 359 acceptance stamp on the bottom flat below the serrations. The safety lever is the correct narrow type, which measures 4mm in width along the arm. The milled out safety recess area on the left side of the slide shows considerable wear. The “F” stamp retains faded red paint while the “S” retains its white paint that has generally turned yellow. The right side of the slide has the correct eagle over 359 Walther acceptance stamp, followed by the eagle over Swastika proof stamp, followed by another Walther over 359 acceptance stamp. The rear site is the correct thick type, which measures 7.10mm wide.

Melonite Nitriding treatment turns a standard chrome moly steel barrel into a very slick, hard 
and corrosion resistant barrel. Unlike chrome lining, the Melonite process is a treatment done 
to the surface instead of adding a layer of material. This treatment is done to both the inside and 
outside of the barrel. The slick surface will never peel, is thicker than chrome lining, will not 
negatively affect accuracy as chrome lining does and will reduce the amount of friction created. 
Less friction equals less bore surface wear which will extend the barrel life. Another added benefit 
is carbon does not easily adhere to this surface making your cleaning job that much easier.  This 
technology has been used by Glock, Springfield and Heckler & Koch for years and is gaining 
popularity as more companies are offering their products with this treatment.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Franchi Black Magic 12 gauge
postcontent:
Very nice gun, awesome condition.  the stock had a hairline crack in it, had it stripped and fixed, then refinished.  very nice dark wood stain.  it is gas operated semi auto, very easy to take apart and clean.  gold trigger and trim in great condition. 3" chamber, chrome-moly ribbed barrel.  i just have zero use for it as i am not a shotgun guy by any means. 

you cannot find this gun for sale anymore.  there are a coupe fake auction sites out there that say they have sold these for 366.00 but that is 100% not true and they say that about everygun to lure you to the site.  please base prices off of gunbroker.com  that is the only acurate site if you must base off of an auction site.  these sold for $600+ when they were in stores.

the reason they are not sold anymore... gas operated shotguns will cycle through any shell clean.  most semi auto shotguns are inertia based and will only cycle through when enough inertia is made from the load.  gas ones cost too much to make when people didnt know the difference between gas and inertia.  so they decided to make 12g models that werent gas and discontinued the gas ones.  still easy to find parts for online, not that you'll need them.

title: For Sale/Trade:  S&W Model 66 (no-dash, early '70's)
location: Harris County/ N. Columbus, Columbus, GA, Georgia
postcontent:
I have a  S&W Model 66 .357 revolver, 4" barrel, that I bought from a dealer at a gunshow here in Columbus several years ago.
The Model 66 is a mid-sized, stainless steel, K-frame .357 magnum ( which, of course, will also fire .38 specials).
This is a straight Model 66 "no dash", meaning it's the very first series of this model, made between 1970 and 1976.
 The pistol is in very good condition, with a few mild dings or abrasions that you'd expect to see on a 40-year old gun, but nothing horrendous, at all.
I originally acquired the pistol with a set of black rubber Pachmayr's on it, but have since put on a set of S&W walnut target grips (w/ checkering and finger grooves, as seen in the photos).
The cyclinder lock-up is VERY tight, and the flame cutting under the top strap is basically just a surface discoloration, there's virtually no etching that I can tell, indicating that it's been fired very little. The crown is perfect, and the rifling is crisp and clean.
I've fired it two, maybe three times myself, it's a great pistol, through and through, and these older pinned and recessed Smith's are only increasing in value and desirability.
 Thanks for looking......

title: For Sale:  WASR-10 ROMANIAN AK-47 7.62X39 W UPGRADES AK47
postcontent:
Like other AKM models, all rifles in the WASR series are made with stamped receivers. WASR's were originally designed to take single-stack magazines. They feature chrome-lined barrels and are sold with wooden, side or under folding stocks. WASR's also come with a side-mount scope rail.

WASR's are imported to the US by Century Arms. Upon importing the rifles century arms mills out the original single stack magazine well to make the rifle take standard (double stack) AK magazines. In order to make the rifle compliant with US section 922r they replace 10 original parts with US manufactured parts. The most noticeable US made part is the plastic pistol grip. Other US parts include the gas piston and the fire control group, which is replaced by a Tapco Trigger group.

The bore has been cleaned inspected by a gunsmith it has "minimal" pitting in one area and could be fired again safely per gunsmith. The overall rifle has very minimal to no pitting. There are also inspectors marks on the barrel that read AW with a P under them.  Also there are inspectors marks VP with the colt stamp.
